Biglari resigns from CCA Industries


By Patrick Danner


        Updated 8:43 pm, Tuesday, July 8, 2014
    












































































































































 


Image 1of/1
CaptionClose



















Image 1 of 1


San Antonio activist investor Sardar Biglari (pictured) and cohort Philip Cooley have abruptly resigned from the board of CCA Industries Inc., a New Jersey-based marketer and manufacturer of health and beauty products. less
San Antonio activist investor Sardar Biglari (pictured) and cohort Philip Cooley have abruptly resigned from the board of CCA Industries Inc., a New Jersey-based marketer and manufacturer of health and beauty ... more










 






Biglari resigns from CCA Industries

1 / 1


Back to Gallery
















SAN ANTONIO — San Antonio activist investor Sardar Biglari and cohort Philip Cooley have abruptly resigned from the board of CCA Industries Inc., a New Jersey-based marketer and manufacturer of health and beauty products.
Biglari, chairman of Biglari Holdings Inc., parent company of Steak 'n Shake restaurants, couldn't be reached for comment. Cooley is vice chairman of Biglari Holdings.



Stephen Heit, CCA's chief financial officer, also couldn't be reached for comment.
Biglari and Cooley joined CCA's board three years ago after Biglari entities acquired a 12.8 percent stake in CCA's common shares.



Business Channel




 
In their resignation letters dated July 1, Biglari and Cooley didn't offer any reasons other than to say they had no disagreement with the company.
Biglari and Cooley had been nominated to serve again as CCA directors. CCA's annual meeting is scheduled for July 17.
CCA has struggled, losing more than $6 million on declining sales in its last fiscal year.


 



















